# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: humidity-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The **dew point** is the temperature that air, of a constant absolute humidity and pressure, must be cooled to in order for the relative humidity to rise to 100%.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] This temperature is a thermodynamic property that depends on the pressure and water content of the air.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] When the air at a temperature above the dew point is cooled, its moisture capacity is reduced, and when the temperature passes below the dew point water vapor will condense, or precipitate, to form liquid water.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] When this occurs through the air's contact with a colder surface, the precipitate on that surface is *dew*.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The dew point is affected by the air's absolute humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The more moisture the air contains, the higher its dew point.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] When the temperature is below the freezing point of water, the dew point is called the **frost point**, as frost is formed via deposition rather than condensation.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] In liquids, the analog to the dew point is the cloud point.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The dew point temperature is an important measure of humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] As the dew point reaches 20 C/70 F degrees, almost everyone feels "sticky".
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Thus the dew point is the best predictor of energy use for cooling in the summer.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] If all the other factors influencing humidity remain constant, at ground level the relative humidity rises as the temperature falls; this is because the air's capacity to hold water vapor decreases, and less vapor is needed to saturate the air.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The dew point temperature equals the air temperature when the air is saturated with water; in all other cases the dew point will be less than the air temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] In technical terms, the dew point is the temperature at which the water vapor in a sample of air at constant barometric pressure condenses into liquid water at the same rate at which it evaporates.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] At temperatures below the dew point, the rate of condensation will be greater than that of evaporation, forming more liquid water.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The condensed water is called dew when it forms on a solid surface, or frost if it freezes.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] In the air, the condensed water is called either fog or a cloud, depending on its altitude when it forms.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] If the temperature is below the dew point, and no dew or fog forms, the vapor is called supersaturated.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] This can happen if there are not enough particles in the air to act as condensation nuclei.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The dew point depends on how much water vapor the air contains.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] If the air is very dry and has few water molecules, the dew point is low and surfaces must be much cooler than the air for condensation to occur.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] If the air is very humid and contains many water molecules, the dew point is high and condensation can occur on surfaces that are only a few degrees cooler than the air.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] A high relative humidity implies that the dew point is close to the current air temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] A relative humidity of 100% indicates the dew point is equal to the current temperature and that the air is maximally saturated with water.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] When the moisture content remains constant and temperature increases, relative humidity decreases, but the dew point remains constant.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] General aviation pilots use dew point data to calculate the likelihood of carburetor icing and fog, and to estimate the height of a cumuliform cloud base.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Increasing the barometric pressure raises the dew point.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] This means that, if the pressure increases, the mass of water vapor per volume unit of air must be reduced in order to maintain the same dew point.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] For example, consider New York City (10 m or 33 ft elevation) and Denver (1610 m or 5280 ft elevation).
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Because Denver is at a higher elevation than New York, it will tend to have a lower barometric pressure.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] This means that if the dew point and temperature in both cities are the same, the amount of water vapor in the air will be greater in Denver.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] When the air temperature is high, the human body uses the evaporation of perspiration to cool down, with the cooling effect directly related to how fast the perspiration evaporates.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The rate at which perspiration can evaporate depends on how much moisture is in the air and how much moisture the air can hold.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] If the air is already saturated with moisture (humid), perspiration will not evaporate.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] As the air surrounding one's body is warmed by body heat, it will rise and be replaced with other air.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] If air is moved away from one's body with a natural breeze or a fan, sweat will evaporate faster, making perspiration more effective at cooling the body, thereby increasing comfort.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] By contrast, comfort decreases as unevaporated perspiration increases.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] A wet bulb thermometer also uses evaporative cooling, so it provides a good measure for use in evaluating comfort level.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Discomfort also exists when the dew point is very low (below around −5 °C or 23 °F).
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The drier air can cause skin to crack and become irritated more easily.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration recommends indoor air be maintained at 20–24.5 °C (68–76 °F) with a 20–60% relative humidity, equivalent to a dew point of approximately 4.0 to 16.5 °C (39 to 62 °F) (by Simple Rule calculation below).
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Lower dew points, less than 10 °C (50 °F), correlate with lower ambient temperatures and cause the body to require less cooling.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] A lower dew point can go along with a high temperature only at extremely low relative humidity, allowing for relatively effective cooling.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] People inhabiting tropical and subtropical climates acclimatize somewhat to higher dew points.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Thus, a resident of Singapore or Miami, for example, might have a higher threshold for discomfort than a resident of a temperate climate like London or Chicago.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] People accustomed to temperate climates often begin to feel uncomfortable when the dew point gets above 15 °C (59 °F), while others might find dew points up to 18 °C (64 °F) comfortable.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Most inhabitants of temperate areas will consider dew points above 21 °C (70 °F) oppressive and tropical-like, while inhabitants of hot and humid areas may not find this uncomfortable.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Thermal comfort depends not just on physical environmental factors, but also on psychological factors.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] A rising air mass in the atmosphere will cool as the pressure reduces: its temperature will move closer to the dew point temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The relative humidity of this air increases as the pressure drops with the same amount of water vapor.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] This combination causes the dew point temperature to fall 0.2 °C per 100 m or 4.5 °F per 1000 ft.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] At the elevation where the dew point is reached condensation begins, creating clouds, or fog as it is called at low altitudes.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Cumulus clouds tend to have flat bottoms marking the altitude where the temperature crosses the dew point.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The condensation of water vapor into water droplets releases 600 calories of energy per gram of water, heating the surrounding air.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Measurement is done by specific devices called "dew point meters".
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] These devices consist of a polished metal mirror which is cooled as air is passed over it.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The dew point is revealed by observing the loss of clarity in the reflection cast by the mirror.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Manual devices of this sort can be used to calibrate other types of humidity sensors, and automatic sensors may be used in a control loop with a humidifier or dehumidifier to control the dew point of the air in a building or in a smaller space for a manufacturing process.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The values of b and c were selected by minimizing the maximum deviation over the range −40 °C to +50 °C.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] There are several different constant sets in use.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] These valuations provide a maximum error of 0.1%, for −30 °C ≤ T ≤ 35°C and 1% < RH < 100% .
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Another common set of values originates from the 1974 *Psychrometry and Psychrometric Charts*.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Also, in the *Journal of Applied Meteorology and Climatology*, Arden Buck provides several different valuation sets, with different maximum errors for different temperature ranges.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] There is also a simple approximation that allows conversion between the dew point, temperature, and relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The derivation of this approach, a discussion of its accuracy, comparisons to other approximations, and more information on the history and applications of the dew point, can be found in an article published in the *Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society*.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] For example, a relative humidity of 100% means dew point is the same as air temp.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] For 90% RH, dew point is 3 °F lower than air temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] For every 10 percent lower, dew point drops 3 °F.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The frost point is similar to the dew point in that it is the temperature to which a given parcel of humid air must be cooled, at constant atmospheric pressure, for water vapor to be deposited on a surface as ice crystals without undergoing the liquid phase (compare with sublimation).
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The frost point for a given parcel of air is always higher than the dew point, as breaking the stronger bonding between water molecules on the surface of ice compared to the surface of (supercooled) liquid water requires a higher temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] In Ancient Greece, Aristotle considered that dew fell from the sky.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] During the Renaissance, Ferdinando II de' Medici built a hygrometer to track the temperature and wind conditions that lead to water formation.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] In the 18th century, Charles Le Roy attempted to determine the dew point by pouring cold water into a glass container.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The first modern theory of dew was composed by William Charles Wells, who published his experiments in his 1818 *Essay on Dew*.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] Meteorologist John Aitken demonstrated in 1887 that dew comes from the earth or from the plants, and does not fall from air.
[src:humidity-sensors/dew-point] The highest dew point ever recorded on Earth is 35 °C (95 °F) (with a temperature of 42 °C (108 °F)), observed at Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, at 3:00 p.m. on 8 July 2003.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humidity depends on the temperature and pressure of the system of interest.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The same amount of water vapor results in higher relative humidity in cool air than warm air.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The amount of water vapor needed to achieve saturation increases as the temperature increases.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] As the temperature of a parcel of air decreases it will eventually reach the saturation point without adding or losing water mass.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The amount of water vapor contained within a parcel of air can vary significantly.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Three primary measurements of humidity are widely employed: absolute, relative, and specific.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] **Absolute humidity** is the mass of water vapor per volume of air (in grams per cubic meter).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] **Relative humidity**, often expressed as a percentage, indicates a present state of absolute humidity relative to a maximum humidity given the same temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] **Specific humidity** is the ratio of water vapor mass to total moist air parcel mass.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humidity plays an important role for surface life.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For animal life dependent on perspiration (sweating) to regulate internal body temperature, high humidity impairs heat exchange efficiency by reducing the rate of moisture evaporation from skin surfaces.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This effect can be calculated using a heat index table, or alternatively using a similar humidex.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The notion of air "holding" water vapor or being "saturated" by it is often mentioned in connection with the concept of relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This, however, is misleading—the amount of water vapor that enters (or can enter) a given space at a given temperature is almost independent of the amount of air (nitrogen, oxygen, etc.) that is present.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Indeed, a vacuum has approximately the same equilibrium capacity to hold water vapor as the same volume filled with air; both are given by the equilibrium vapor pressure of water at the given temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] There is a very small difference described under "Enhancement factor" below, which can be neglected in many calculations unless great accuracy is required.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Absolute humidity usually denotes the volumetric absolute humidity, which is the total mass of water vapor (gas form of water) present in a given volume or mass of air.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] It does not take temperature into consideration.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Absolute humidity in the atmosphere ranges from near zero to roughly 30 g (1.1 oz) per cubic metre when the air is saturated at 30 °C (86 °F).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This makes the (volumetric) absolute humidity unsuitable for some applications.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Air is a gas, and the volume of a specific amount varies with pressure and temperature, per Boyle's law.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Because of the variability of absolute humidity with changes in air temperature or pressure, use of the absolute humidity as defined above is inappropriate for computations in chemical engineering, such as drying, where temperature variations might be significant.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] As a result, absolute humidity in chemical engineering may refer to mass of water vapor per unit mass of dry air, also known as the "humidity ratio" or "mass mixing ratio" (see also Specific humidity below), which is better suited for heat and mass balance calculations.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The ratio of the mass of water per unit volume as defined in the equation above is also called the "volumetric humidity", which may be the preferred term in such contexts.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Because of the potential confusion, British Standard BS 1339 recommends avoiding the term "absolute humidity", deprecating it in favor of "volumetric humidity", "specific humidity", and "mixing ratio".
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In general, when using absolute humidity, units should always be carefully checked to determine whether the volumetric or specific humidity is being used; many humidity charts are given in g/kg or kg/kg, but any mass units may be used.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Relative humidity is the ratio of how much water vapour is in the air to how much water vapour the air could potentially contain at a given temperature and pressure.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] More formally, relative humidity is defined as the ratio of the partial pressure of water vapor to the equilibrium vapor pressure of water at the same temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] where Ps is the saturation pressure of water at temperature T1.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Relative humidity varies with any change in the temperature or pressure of the air: colder air can contain less vapour, and water will tend to condense out of the air more at lower temperatures.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] So changing the temperature of air can change the relative humidity, even when the specific humidity remains constant.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] If two parcels of air have the same specific humidity and temperature but different pressures, the parcel at the higher pressure will have the higher relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Cooling air increases the relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] If the relative humidity rises to 100% (the dew point) and there is an available surface or particle, the water vapour will condense into liquid or deposit into ice.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Likewise, warming air decreases the relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Warming some air containing a fog may cause that fog to evaporate, as the droplets are prone to total evaporation due to the lowering partial pressure of water vapour in that air, as the temperature rises.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Relative humidity only considers the invisible water vapour.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Mists, clouds, fogs and aerosols of water do not count towards the measure of relative humidity of the air, although their presence is an indication that a body of air may be close to the dew point.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Relative humidity is normally expressed as a percentage; a higher percentage means that the air–water mixture is more humid.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] At 100% relative humidity, the air is saturated and is at its dew point.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In the absence of a foreign body on which droplets or crystals can nucleate, the relative humidity can exceed 100%, in which case the air is said to be supersaturated.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Introduction of some particles or a surface to a body of air above 100% relative humidity will allow condensation or ice to form on those nuclei, thereby removing some of the vapour and lowering the humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Relative humidity is an important metric used in weather forecasts and reports, as it is an indicator of the likelihood of precipitation, dew, or fog.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In hot summer weather, a rise in relative humidity increases the apparent temperature to humans (and other animals) by hindering the evaporation of perspiration from the skin.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For example, according to the *heat index*, a relative humidity of 75% at air temperature of 80.0 °F (26.7 °C) would feel like 83.6 ± 1.3 °F (28.7 ± 0.7 °C).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Because wood changes shape with changes in humidity, relative humidity is used to evaluate moisture content and size changes in wood, such as making allowances for seasonal movement in wood floors.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The term *relative humidity* is reserved for systems of water vapor in air.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The term *relative saturation* is used to describe the analogous property for systems consisting of a condensable phase other than water in a non-condensable phase other than air.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] A device used to measure humidity of air is called a psychrometer or hygrometer (not to be confused with Hydrometer).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] A humidistat is a humidity-triggered switch, often used to control a humidifier or a dehumidifier.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The humidity of an air and water vapor mixture is determined through the use of psychrometric charts if both the dry bulb temperature (*T*) and the wet bulb temperature (*T*w) of the mixture are known.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] These quantities are readily estimated by using a sling psychrometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] There are several empirical formulas that can be used to estimate the equilibrium vapor pressure of water vapor as a function of temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The Antoine equation is among the least complex of these, having only three parameters (*A*, *B*, and *C*).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Other formulas, such as the Goff–Gratch equation and the Magnus–Tetens approximation, are more complicated but yield better accuracy.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Buck has reported that the maximal relative error is less than 0.20% between −20 and +50 °C (−4 and 122 °F) when this particular form of the generalized formula is used to estimate the equilibrium vapor pressure of water.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] There are various devices used to measure and regulate humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Calibration standards for the most accurate measurement include the gravimetric hygrometer, chilled mirror hygrometer, and electrolytic hygrometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The gravimetric method, while the most accurate, is very cumbersome.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For fast and very accurate measurement the chilled mirror method is effective.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For process on-line measurements, the most commonly used sensors nowadays are based on capacitance measurements to measure relative humidity, frequently with internal conversions to display absolute humidity as well.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] These are cheap, simple, generally accurate and relatively robust.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] All humidity sensors face problems in measuring dust-laden gas, such as exhaust streams from clothes dryers.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humidity is also measured on a global scale using remotely placed satellites.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] These satellites are able to detect the concentration of water in the troposphere at altitudes between 4 and 12 km (2.5 and 7.5 mi).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Satellites that can measure water vapor have sensors that are sensitive to infrared radiation.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Water vapor specifically absorbs and re-radiates radiation in this spectral band.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Satellite water vapor imagery plays an important role in monitoring climate conditions (like the formation of thunderstorms) and in the development of weather forecasts.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humidity depends on water vaporization and condensation, which, in turn, mainly depends on temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Therefore, when applying more pressure to a gas saturated with water, all components will initially decrease in volume approximately according to the *ideal gas law*.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] However, some of the water will condense until returning to almost the same humidity as before, giving the resulting total volume deviating from what the ideal gas law predicted.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Conversely, decreasing temperature would also make some water condense, again making the final volume deviate from predicted by the ideal gas law.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Therefore, gas volume may alternatively be expressed as the dry volume, excluding the humidity content.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This fraction more accurately follows the ideal gas law.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] On the contrary the saturated volume is the volume a gas mixture would have if humidity was added to it until saturation (or 100% relative humidity).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humid air is less dense than dry air because a molecule of water (*m* ≈ 18 Da) is less massive than either a molecule of nitrogen (*m* ≈ 28) or a molecule of oxygen (*m* ≈ 32).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] About 78% of the molecules in dry air are nitrogen (N2).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Another 21% of the molecules in dry air are oxygen (O2).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The final 1% of dry air is a mixture of other gases.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For any gas, at a given temperature and pressure, the number of molecules present in a particular volume is constant.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Therefore, when some number N of water molecules (vapor) is introduced into a volume of dry air, the number of air molecules in that volume must decrease by the same number N for the pressure to remain constant without using a change in temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The numbers are exactly equal if we consider the gases as ideal.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The addition of water molecules, or any other molecules, to a gas, without removal of an equal number of other molecules, will necessarily require a change in temperature, pressure, or total volume; that is, a change in *at least* one of these three parameters.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] If temperature and pressure remain constant, the volume increases, and the dry air molecules that were displaced will initially move out into the additional volume, after which the mixture will eventually become uniform through diffusion.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Hence the mass per unit volume of the gas—its density—decreases.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Isaac Newton discovered this phenomenon and wrote about it in his book *Opticks*.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The relative humidity of an air–water system is dependent not only on the temperature but also on the absolute pressure of the system of interest.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This dependence is demonstrated by considering the air–water system shown below.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The system is closed (i.e., no matter enters or leaves the system).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] If the system at State A is isobarically heated (heating with no change in system pressure), then the relative humidity of the system decreases because the equilibrium vapor pressure of water increases with increasing temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] If the system at State A is isothermally compressed (compressed with no change in system temperature), then the relative humidity of the system increases because the partial pressure of water in the system increases with the volume reduction.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Above 202.64 kPa, the RH would exceed 100% and water may begin to condense.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] If the pressure of State A was changed by simply adding more dry air, without changing the volume, the relative humidity would not change.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Therefore, a change in relative humidity can be explained by a change in system temperature, a change in the volume of the system, or change in both of these system properties.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The enhancement factor is equal to unity for ideal gas systems.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] However, in real systems, the interaction effects between gas molecules result in a small increase of the equilibrium vapor pressure of water in air relative to equilibrium vapor pressure of pure water vapor.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Therefore, the enhancement factor is normally slightly greater than unity for real systems.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The enhancement factor is commonly used to correct the equilibrium vapor pressure of water vapor when empirical relationships, such as those developed by Wexler, Goff, and Gratch, are used to estimate the properties of psychrometric systems.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Buck has reported that, at sea level, the vapor pressure of water in saturated moist air amounts to an increase of approximately 0.5% over the equilibrium vapor pressure of pure water.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] While humidity itself is a climate variable, it also affects other climate variables.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Environmental humidity is affected by winds and by rainfall.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The most humid cities on Earth are generally located closer to the equator, near coastal regions.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Cities in parts of Asia and Oceania are among the most humid.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Bangkok, Ho Chi Minh City, Kuala Lumpur, Hong Kong, Manila, Jakarta, Naha, Singapore, Kaohsiung and Taipei have very high humidity most or all year round because of their proximity to water bodies and the equator and often overcast weather.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Some places experience extreme humidity during their rainy seasons combined with warmth giving the feel of a lukewarm sauna, such as Kolkata, Chennai and Kochi in India, and Lahore in Pakistan.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Sukkur city located on the Indus River in Pakistan has some of the highest and most uncomfortable dew points in the country, frequently exceeding 30 °C (86 °F) in the monsoon season.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] High temperatures combine with the high dew point to create heat index in excess of 65 °C (149 °F).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Darwin experiences an extremely humid wet season from December to April.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Houston, Miami, Osaka, Shanghai, Shenzhen and Tokyo also have an extreme humid period in their summer months.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] During the South-west and North-east Monsoon seasons (respectively, late May to September and November to March), expect heavy rains and a relatively high humidity post-rainfall.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Outside the monsoon seasons, humidity is high (in comparison to countries further from the Equator), but completely sunny days abound.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In cooler places such as Northern Tasmania, Australia, high humidity is experienced all year due to the ocean between mainland Australia and Tasmania.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In the summer the hot dry air is absorbed by this ocean and the temperature rarely climbs above 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humidity affects the energy budget and thereby influences temperatures in two major ways.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] First, water vapor in the atmosphere contains "latent" energy.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] During transpiration or evaporation, this latent heat is removed from surface liquid, cooling the Earth's surface.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This is the biggest non-radiative cooling effect at the surface.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] It compensates for roughly 70% of the average net radiative warming at the surface.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Second, water vapor is the most abundant of all greenhouse gases.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Water vapor, like a green lens that allows green light to pass through it but absorbs red light, is a "selective absorber".
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Like the other greenhouse gasses, water vapor is transparent to most solar energy.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] However, it absorbs the infrared energy emitted (radiated) upward by the Earth's surface, which is the reason that humid areas experience very little nocturnal cooling but dry desert regions cool considerably at night.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This selective absorption causes the greenhouse effect.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] It raises the surface temperature substantially above its theoretical radiative equilibrium temperature with the sun, and water vapor is the cause of more of this warming than any other greenhouse gas.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Unlike most other greenhouse gases, however, water is not merely below its boiling point in all regions of the Earth, but below its freezing point at many altitudes.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] As a condensible greenhouse gas, it precipitates, with a much lower scale height and shorter atmospheric lifetime – weeks instead of decades.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Without other greenhouse gases, Earth's blackbody temperature, below the freezing point of water, would cause water vapor to be removed from the atmosphere.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Water vapor is thus a "slave" to the non-condensible greenhouse gases.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humidity is one of the fundamental abiotic factors that defines any habitat (the tundra, wetlands, and the desert are a few examples), and is a determinant of which animals and plants can thrive in a given environment.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The human body dissipates heat through perspiration and its evaporation.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Heat convection, to the surrounding air, and thermal radiation are the primary modes of heat transport from the body.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Under conditions of high humidity, the rate of evaporation of sweat from the skin decreases.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Also, if the atmosphere is as warm or warmer than the skin during times of high humidity, blood brought to the body surface cannot dissipate heat by conduction to the air.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] With so much blood going to the external surface of the body, less goes to the active muscles, the brain, and other internal organs.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Physical strength declines, and fatigue occurs sooner than it would otherwise.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Alertness and mental capacity also may be affected, resulting in *heat stroke* or hyperthermia.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Domesticated plants and animals (e.g. lizards) require regular upkeep of humidity percent when grown in-home and container conditions, for optimal thriving environment.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Although humidity is an important factor for thermal comfort, humans are more sensitive to variations in temperature than they are to changes in relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humidity has a small effect on thermal comfort outdoors when air temperatures are low, a slightly more pronounced effect at moderate air temperatures, and a much stronger influence at higher air temperatures.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humans are sensitive to humid air because the human body uses evaporative cooling as the primary mechanism to regulate temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Under humid conditions, the *rate* at which perspiration evaporates on the skin is lower than it would be under arid conditions.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Because humans perceive the rate of heat transfer from the body rather than temperature itself, we feel warmer when the relative humidity is high than when it is low.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Humans can be comfortable within a wide range of humidities depending on the temperature—from 30 to 70%—but ideally not above the Absolute (60 °F Dew Point), between 40% and 60%.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In general, higher temperatures will require lower humidities to achieve thermal comfort compared to lower temperatures, with all other factors held constant.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For example, with clothing level = 1, metabolic rate = 1.1, and air speed 0.1 m/s, a change in air temperature and mean radiant temperature from 20 °C to 24 °C would lower the maximum acceptable relative humidity from 100% to 65% to maintain thermal comfort conditions.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The CBE Thermal Comfort Tool can be used to demonstrate the effect of relative humidity for specific thermal comfort conditions and it can be used to demonstrate compliance with ASHRAE Standard 55–2017.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Some people experience difficulty breathing in humid environments.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Some cases are related to respiratory conditions such as asthma, where humidity as low as 50% was shown to meaningfully increase risks for dyspnea, cough and exercise induced bronchoconstriction.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Other cases may be the product of anxiety.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Affected people will often hyperventilate in response, causing sensations of numbness, faintness, and loss of concentration, among others.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Air conditioning reduces discomfort by reducing not just temperature but humidity as well.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Heating cold outdoor air can decrease relative humidity levels indoors to below 30%.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] According to ASHRAE Standard 55-2017: Thermal Environmental Conditions for Human Occupancy, indoor thermal comfort can be achieved through the PMV method with relative humidities ranging from 0% to 100%, depending on the levels of the other factors contributing to thermal comfort.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] However, the recommended range of indoor relative humidity in air conditioned buildings is generally 30–60%.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Very low humidity can create discomfort, respiratory problems, and aggravate allergies in some individuals.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Low humidity causes tissue lining nasal passages to dry, crack and become more susceptible to penetration of rhinovirus cold viruses.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Extremely low (below 20 %) relative humidities may also cause eye irritation.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The use of a humidifier in homes, especially bedrooms, can help with these symptoms.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Indoor relative humidities kept above 30% reduce the likelihood of the occupant's nasal passages drying out, especially in winter.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Excess moisture in buildings expose occupants to fungal spores, cell fragments, or mycotoxins.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Infants in homes with mold have a much greater risk of developing asthma and allergic rhinitis.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] More than half of adult workers in moldy/humid buildings develop nasal or sinus symptoms due to mold exposure.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] High humidity may adversely impact people with asthma, where humidity as low as 50% was shown to meaningfully increase risks for dyspnea, cough and exercise induced bronchoconstriction.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Exercise induced symptoms pose a significant challenge, while physical exercise and weight loss (to normal) are important parts in management.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Mucociliary clearance in the respiratory tract is also hindered by low humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] One study in dogs found that mucus transport was lower at an absolute humidity of 9 g/m3 than at 30 g/m3.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Increased humidity can also lead to changes in total body water that usually leads to moderate weight gain, especially if one is acclimated to working or exercising in hot and humid weather.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Common construction methods often produce building enclosures with a poor thermal boundary, requiring an insulation and air barrier system designed to retain indoor environmental conditions while resisting external environmental conditions.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The energy-efficient, heavily sealed architecture introduced in the 20th century also sealed off the movement of moisture, and this has resulted in a secondary problem of condensation forming in and around walls, which encourages the development of mold and mildew.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Additionally, buildings with foundations not properly sealed will allow water to flow through the walls due to capillary action of pores found in masonry products.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Solutions for energy-efficient buildings that avoid condensation are a current topic of architecture.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For climate control in buildings using HVAC systems, the key is to maintain the relative humidity at a comfortable range—low enough to be comfortable but high enough to avoid problems associated with very dry air.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] When the temperature is high and the relative humidity is low, evaporation of water is rapid; soil dries, wet clothes hung on a line or rack dry quickly, and perspiration readily evaporates from the skin.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Wooden furniture can shrink, causing the paint that covers these surfaces to fracture.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] When the temperature is low and the relative humidity is high, evaporation of water is slow.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] When relative humidity approaches 100%, condensation can occur on surfaces, leading to problems with mold, corrosion, decay, and other moisture-related deterioration.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Condensation can pose a safety risk as it can promote the growth of mold and wood rot as well as possibly freezing emergency exits shut.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Certain production and technical processes and treatments in factories, laboratories, hospitals, and other facilities require specific relative humidity levels to be maintained using humidifiers, dehumidifiers and associated control systems.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The basic principles for buildings, above, also apply to vehicles.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In addition, there may be safety considerations.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For instance, high humidity inside a vehicle can lead to problems of condensation, such as misting of windshields and shorting of electrical components.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In vehicles and pressure vessels such as pressurized airliners, submersibles and spacecraft, these considerations may be critical to safety, and complex environmental control systems including equipment to maintain pressure are needed.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Airliners operate with low internal relative humidity, often under 20%, especially on long flights.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The low humidity is a consequence of drawing in the very cold air with a low absolute humidity, which is found at airliner cruising altitudes.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Subsequent warming of this air lowers its relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This causes discomfort such as sore eyes, dry skin, and drying out of mucosa, but humidifiers are not employed to raise it to comfortable mid-range levels because the volume of water required to be carried on board can be a significant weight penalty.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] As airliners descend from colder altitudes into warmer air, perhaps even flying through clouds a few thousand feet above the ground, the ambient relative humidity can increase dramatically.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Some of this moist air is usually drawn into the pressurized aircraft cabin and into other non-pressurized areas of the aircraft and condenses on the cold aircraft skin.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Liquid water can usually be seen running along the aircraft skin, both on the inside and outside of the cabin.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Because of the drastic changes in relative humidity inside the vehicle, components must be qualified to operate in those environments.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The recommended environmental qualifications for most commercial aircraft components is listed in RTCA DO-160.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Cold, humid air can promote the formation of ice, which is a danger to aircraft as it affects the wing profile and increases weight.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Naturally aspirated internal combustion engines have a further danger of ice forming inside the carburetor.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Aviation weather reports (METARs) therefore include an indication of relative humidity, usually in the form of the dew point.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Pilots must take humidity into account when calculating takeoff distances, because high humidity requires longer runways and will decrease climb performance.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] "Density Altitude" is the pressure altitude adjusted for non-standard temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] An increase in temperature, and, to a much lesser degree, humidity, will cause an increase in density altitude.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Thus, in hot and humid conditions, the density altitude at a particular location may be significantly higher than the true altitude.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Electronic devices are often rated to operate only under certain humidity conditions (e.g., 10% to 90%).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The optimal humidity for electronic devices is 30% to 65%.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] At the top end of the range, moisture may increase the conductivity of permeable insulators leading to malfunction.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Too low humidity may make materials brittle.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] A particular danger to electronic items, regardless of the stated operating humidity range, is condensation.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] When an electronic item is moved from a cold place (e.g., garage, car, shed, air conditioned space in the tropics) to a warm humid place (house, outside tropics), condensation may coat circuit boards and other insulators, leading to short circuit inside the equipment.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Such short circuits may cause substantial permanent damage if the equipment is powered on before the condensation has evaporated.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] A similar condensation effect can often be observed when a person wearing glasses comes in from the cold (i.e. the glasses become foggy).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] It is advisable to allow electronic equipment to acclimatise for several hours, after being brought in from the cold, before powering on.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Some electronic devices can detect such a change and indicate, when plugged in and usually with a small droplet symbol, that they cannot be used until the risk from condensation has passed.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In situations where time is critical, increasing air flow through the device's internals, such as removing the side panel from a PC case and directing a fan to blow into the case, will significantly reduce the time needed to acclimatise to the new environment.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In contrast, a very low humidity level favors the build-up of static electricity, which may result in spontaneous shutdown of computers when discharges occur.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Apart from spurious erratic function, electrostatic discharges can cause dielectric breakdown in solid-state devices, resulting in irreversible damage.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Data centers often monitor relative humidity levels for these reasons.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] High humidity can often have a negative effect on the capacity of chemical plants and refineries that use furnaces as part of a certain processes (e.g., steam reforming, wet sulfuric acid processes).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For example, because humidity reduces ambient oxygen concentrations (dry air is typically 20.9% oxygen, but at 100% relative humidity the air is 20.4% oxygen), flue gas fans must intake air at a higher rate than would otherwise be required to maintain the same firing rate.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] High humidity in the oven, represented by an elevated wet-bulb temperature, increases the thermal conductivity of the air around the baked item, leading to a quicker baking process or even burning.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Conversely, low humidity slows the baking process down.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] At 100% relative humidity, air is saturated and at its dew point: the water vapor pressure would permit neither evaporation of nearby liquid water nor condensation to grow the nearby water; neither sublimation of nearby ice nor deposition to grow the nearby ice.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Relative humidity can exceed 100%, in which case the air is supersaturated.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Cloud formation requires supersaturated air.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Cloud condensation nuclei lower the level of supersaturation required to form fogs and clouds – in the absence of nuclei around which droplets or ice can form, a higher level of supersaturation is required for these droplets or ice crystals to form spontaneously.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In the Wilson cloud chamber, which is used in nuclear physics experiments, a state of supersaturation is created within the chamber, and moving subatomic particles act as condensation nuclei so trails of fog show the paths of those particles.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For a given dew point and its corresponding absolute humidity, the relative humidity will change inversely, albeit nonlinearly, with the temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This is because the vapor pressure of water increases with temperature—the operative principle behind everything from hair dryers to dehumidifiers.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Due to the increasing potential for a higher water vapor partial pressure at higher air temperatures, the water content of air at sea level can get as high as 3% by mass at 30 °C (86 °F) compared to no more than about 0.5% by mass at 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This explains the low levels (in the absence of measures to add moisture) of humidity in heated structures during winter, resulting in dry skin, itchy eyes, and persistence of static electric charges.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Even with saturation (100% relative humidity) outdoors, heating of infiltrated outside air that comes indoors raises its moisture capacity, which lowers relative humidity and increases evaporation rates from moist surfaces indoors, including human bodies and household plants.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Similarly, during summer in humid climates a great deal of liquid water condenses from air cooled in air conditioners.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Warmer air is cooled below its dew point, and the excess water vapor condenses.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This phenomenon is the same as that which causes water droplets to form on the outside of a cup containing an ice-cold drink.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] A useful rule of thumb is that the maximum absolute humidity doubles for every 20 °F (11 °C) increase in temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Thus, the relative humidity will drop by a factor of 2 for each 20 °F (11 °C) increase in temperature, assuming conservation of absolute moisture.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] For example, in the range of normal temperatures, air at 68 °F (20 °C) and 50% relative humidity will become saturated if cooled to 50 °F (10 °C), its dew point, and 41 °F (5 °C) air at 80% relative humidity warmed to 68 °F (20 °C) will have a relative humidity of only 29% and feel dry.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] By comparison, thermal comfort standard ASHRAE 55 requires systems designed to control humidity to maintain a dew point of 16.8 °C (62.2 °F) though no lower humidity limit is established.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Water vapor is a lighter gas than other gaseous components of air at the same temperature, so humid air will tend to rise by natural convection.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This is a mechanism behind thunderstorms and other weather phenomena.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] Relative humidity is often mentioned in weather forecasts and reports, as it is an indicator of the likelihood of dew, or fog.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] In hot summer weather, it also increases the apparent temperature to humans (and other animals) by hindering the evaporation of perspiration from the skin as the relative humidity rises.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] This effect is calculated as the heat index or humidex.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] A device used to measure humidity is called a hygrometer (not to be confused with Hydrometer); one used to regulate it is called a humidistat, or sometimes hygrostat.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] These are analogous to a thermometer and thermostat for temperature, respectively.
[src:humidity-sensors/humidity] The field concerned with the study of physical and thermodynamic properties of gas–vapor mixtures is named psychrometrics.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A **hygrometer** is an instrument that measures humidity, that is, how much water vapor is present in the air.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Humidity measurement instruments usually rely on measurements of some other quantities, such as temperature, pressure, mass, and mechanical or electrical changes in a substance as moisture is absorbed.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] By calibration and calculation, these measured quantities can be used to indicate the humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Modern electronic devices use the temperature of condensation (called the dew point), or they sense changes in electrical capacitance or resistance.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The maximum amount of water vapor that can be present in a given volume (at saturation) varies greatly with temperature; at low temperatures a lower mass of water per unit volume can remain as vapor than at high temperatures.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Thus a change in the temperature changes the relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A prototype hygrometer was invented by Leonardo da Vinci in 1480.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Major improvements occurred during the 1600s; Francesco Folli invented a more practical version of the device, and Robert Hooke improved a number of meteorological devices, including the hygrometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A more modern version was created by Swiss polymath Johann Heinrich Lambert in 1755.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Later, in the year 1783, Swiss physicist and geologist Horace Bénédict de Saussure invented a hygrometer that uses a stretched human hair as its sensor.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] In the late 17th century, some scientists called humidity-measuring instruments *hygroscopes*; that word is no longer in use, but *hygroscopic* and *hygroscopy*, which derive from it, still are.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Crude hygrometers were devised and developed during the Shang dynasty in Ancient China to study weather.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The Chinese used a bar of charcoal and a lump of earth: its dry weight was taken, then compared with its damp weight after being exposed in the air.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The differences in weight were used to tally the humidity level.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Other techniques were applied using mass to measure humidity, such as when the air was dry, the bar of charcoal would be light, while when the air was humid, the bar of charcoal would be heavy.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] By hanging a lump of earth on one end of a staff and a bar of charcoal on the other end and attaching a fixed lifting string to the middle point to make the staff horizontal in dry air, an ancient hygrometer was made.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The metal-paper coil hygrometer is very useful for giving a dial indication of humidity changes.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] It appears most often in inexpensive devices, and its accuracy is limited, with variations of 10% or more.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] In these devices, water vapor is absorbed by a salt-impregnated paper strip attached to a metal coil, causing the coil to change shape.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] These changes (analogous to those in a bimetallic thermometer) cause an indication on a dial.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] There is usually a metal needle on the front of the gauge that points to a scale.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] These devices use a human or animal hair under some tension.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] (Whalebone and other materials may be used in place of hair.) The hair is hygroscopic (tending toward retaining moisture); its length changes with humidity, and the length change may be magnified by a mechanism and indicated on a dial or scale.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Swiss physicist and geologist Horace Bénédict de Saussure was the first to build such a hygrometer, in 1783.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The traditional folk art device known as a weather house also works on this principle.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The pulley is connected to an index which moves over a graduated scale (e).
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The instrument can be made more sensitive by removing oils from the hair, such as by first soaking the hair in diethyl ether.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A psychrometer, or a wet and dry-bulb thermometer, consists of two calibrated thermometers, one that is dry and one that is kept moist with distilled water on a sock or wick.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] At temperatures above the freezing point of water, evaporation of water from the wick lowers the temperature, such that the wet-bulb thermometer will be at a lower temperature than that of the dry-bulb thermometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] When the air temperature is below freezing, however, the wet-bulb must be covered with a thin coating of ice, in order to be accurate.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] As a result of the heat of sublimation, the wet-bulb temperature will eventually be lower than the dry bulb, although this may take many minutes of continued use of the psychrometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Relative humidity (RH) is computed from the ambient temperature, shown by the dry-bulb thermometer and the difference in temperatures as shown by the wet-bulb and dry-bulb thermometers.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Relative humidity can also be determined by locating the intersection of the wet and dry-bulb temperatures on a psychrometric chart.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The dry and wet thermometers coincide when the air is fully saturated, and the greater the difference the drier the air.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Psychrometers are commonly used in meteorology, and in the heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) industry for proper refrigerant charging of residential and commercial air conditioning systems.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A sling psychrometer, which uses thermometers attached to a handle, is manually spun in free air flow until both temperatures stabilize.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] This is sometimes used for field measurements but is being replaced by more convenient electronic sensors.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A whirling psychrometer uses the same principle, but the two thermometers are fitted into a device that resembles a ratchet or football rattle.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Dew point is the temperature at which a sample of moist air (or any other water vapor) at constant pressure reaches water vapor saturation.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] At this saturation temperature, further cooling results in condensation of water.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Chilled mirror dewpoint hygrometers are some of the most precise instruments commonly available.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] They use a chilled mirror and optoelectronic mechanism to detect condensation on the mirror's surface.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The temperature of the mirror is controlled by electronic feedback to maintain a dynamic equilibrium between evaporation and condensation, thus closely measuring the dew point temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] An accuracy of 0.2 °C is attainable with these devices, which correlates at typical office environments to a relative humidity accuracy of about ±1.2%.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Older chilled-mirrors used a metallic mirror that needed cleaning and skilled labor.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Newer implementations of chilled-mirrors use highly polished surfaces that do not require routine cleaning.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] More recently, spectroscopic chilled-mirrors have been introduced.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Using this method, the dew point is determined with spectroscopic light detection which ascertains the nature of the condensation.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] This method avoids many of the pitfalls of the previous chilled-mirrors and is capable of operating drift free.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Chilled-mirrors remain the reference measurement for calibration of other hygrometers.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] When cost, space, or fragility are important, other types of electronic sensors are used, at the price of lower accuracy.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Capacitive hygrometers measure the effect of humidity on the dielectric constant of a polymer or a metal oxide.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] When calibrated, their accuracy at relative humidities between 5% and 95% is ±2% RH; uncalibrated, this is two to three times worse.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Capacitive sensors are robust against effects such as condensation and temporary high temperatures, but subject to contamination, drift and aging effects.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] They are, however, suitable for many applications.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] In resistive hygrometers, the change in electrical resistance of a material due to humidity is measured.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Typical materials are salts and conductive polymers.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Resistive sensors are less sensitive than capacitive sensors – the change in material properties is less, so they require more complex circuitry.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The material properties also tend to depend both on humidity and temperature, which means in practice that the sensor must be combined with a temperature sensor.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The accuracy and robustness against condensation vary depending on the chosen resistive material.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Robust, condensation-resistant sensors exist with an accuracy of up to ±3% RH (relative humidity).
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] In thermal hygrometers, the change in thermal conductivity of air due to humidity is measured.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] These sensors measure absolute humidity rather than relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A gravimetric hygrometer extracts the water from the air (or other gas) and weighs it separately, for example by weighing a desiccant before and after it has absorbed the water.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The temperature, pressure and volume of the resulting dry gas are also measured, providing enough information to calculate the amount of water per mole of gas.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] This is considered the most accurate primary method of measuring absolute humidity, and national standards based on it have been developed in US, UK, EU and Japan.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] However, the inconvenience of using such devices means they are usually only used to calibrate less accurate instruments, called Transfer Standards.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] An optical hygrometer measures the absorption of light by water in the air.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A light emitter and a light detector are arranged with a volume of air between them.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The attenuation of the light, as seen by the detector, indicates the humidity, according to the Beer–Lambert law.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Aside from greenhouses and industrial spaces, hygrometers are also used in some incubators, saunas, humidors and museums.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] They are also used in the care of wooden musical instruments such as pianos, guitars, violins, and harps which can be damaged by improper humidity conditions.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Hygrometers play a big part in firefighting as the lower the relative humidity, the more vigorously fuels may burn.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] In residential settings, hygrometers are used to assist in humidity control (too low humidity can damage human skin and body, while too high humidity favors growth of mildew and dust mite).
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Hygrometers are also used in the coating industry because the application of paint and other coatings may be very sensitive to humidity and dew point.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Humidity measurement is among the most difficult problems in basic metrology.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] According to the WMO Guide, "The achievable accuracies [for humidity determination] listed in the table refer to good quality instruments that are well operated and maintained.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] In practice, these are not easy to achieve." Two thermometers can be compared by immersing them both in an insulated vessel of water (or alcohol, for temperatures below the freezing point of water) and stirring vigorously to minimize temperature variations.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A high-quality liquid-in-glass thermometer if handled with care should remain stable for some years.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Hygrometers must be calibrated in air, which is a much less effective heat transfer medium than is water, and many types are subject to drift so need regular recalibration.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] In a cold and humid environment, ice may sublimate on the sensor head, whether it is a hair, dew cell, mirror, capacitance sensing element, or dry-bulb thermometer of an aspiration psychrometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The ice on the probe matches the reading to the saturation humidity with respect to ice at that temperature, i.e. the frost point.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] However, a conventional hygrometer is unable to measure properly under the frost point, and the only way to go around this fundamental problem is to use a heated humidity probe.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Accurate calibration of the thermometers used is fundamental to precise humidity determination by the wet-dry method.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] The thermometers must be protected from radiant heat and must have a sufficiently high flow of air over the wet bulb for the most accurate results.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Air is drawn through the tubes with a fan that is driven by a clockwork mechanism to ensure a consistent speed (some modern versions use an electric fan with electronic speed control).
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] One solution sometimes used for accurate humidity measurement when the air temperature is below freezing is to use a thermostatically controlled electric heater to raise the temperature of outside air to above freezing.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] In this arrangement, a fan draws outside air past (1) a thermometer to measure the ambient dry-bulb temperature, (2) the heating element, (3) a second thermometer to measure the dry-bulb temperature of the heated air, then finally (4) a wet-bulb thermometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] According to the World Meteorological Organization Guide, "The principle of the heated psychrometer is that the water vapor content of an air mass does not change if it is heated.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] This property may be exploited to the advantage of the psychrometer by avoiding the need to maintain an ice bulb under freezing conditions.".
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Since the humidity of the ambient air is calculated indirectly from three temperature measurements, in such a device accurate thermometer calibration is even more important than for a two-bulb configuration.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Various researchers have investigated the use of saturated salt solutions for calibrating hygrometers.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Slushy mixtures of certain pure salts and distilled water have the property that they maintain an approximately constant humidity in a closed container.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] A saturated table salt (sodium chloride) bath will eventually give a reading of approximately 75%.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Other salts have other equilibrium humidity levels: Lithium chloride ~11%; Magnesium chloride ~33%; Potassium carbonate ~43%; Potassium sulfate ~97%.
[src:humidity-sensors/hygrometer] Salt solutions will vary somewhat in humidity with temperature and they can take relatively long times to come to equilibrium, but their ease of use compensates somewhat for these disadvantages in low precision applications, such as checking mechanical and electronic hygrometers.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] With the inventions of the hygrometer and thermometer, the theories of combining the two began to emerge during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] In 1818, a German inventor, Ernst Ferdinand August (1795-1870), patented the term “psychrometer”, from the Greek language meaning “cold measure”.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The psychrometer is a hygrometric instrument based on the principle that dry air enhances evaporation, unlike wet air, which slows it.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Although the principles of psychrometry apply to any physical system consisting of gas-vapor mixtures, the most common system of interest is the mixture of water vapor and air, because of its application in heating, ventilation, and air-conditioning and meteorology.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] In human terms, our thermal comfort is in large part a consequence of not just the temperature of the surrounding air, but (because we cool ourselves via perspiration) the extent to which that air is saturated with water vapor.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Many substances are hygroscopic, meaning they attract water, usually in proportion to the relative humidity or above a critical relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Such substances include cotton, paper, cellulose, other wood products, sugar, calcium oxide (burned lime) and many chemicals and fertilizers.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Industries that use these materials are concerned with relative humidity control in production and storage of such materials.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Relative humidity is often controlled in manufacturing areas where flammable materials are handled, to avoid fires caused by the static electricity discharges that can occur in very dry air.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] In industrial drying applications, such as drying paper, manufacturers usually try to achieve an optimum between low relative humidity, which increases the drying rate, and energy usage, which decreases as exhaust relative humidity increases.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] In many industrial applications it is important to avoid condensation that would ruin product or cause corrosion.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Molds and fungi can be controlled by keeping relative humidity low.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Wood destroying fungi generally do not grow at relative humidities below 75%.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The dry-bulb temperature is the temperature indicated by a thermometer exposed to the air in a place sheltered from direct solar radiation.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The term dry-bulb is customarily added to temperature to distinguish it from wet-bulb and dew point temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] In meteorology and psychrometrics the word temperature by itself without a prefix usually means dry-bulb temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Technically, the temperature registered by the dry-bulb thermometer of a psychrometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The name implies that the sensing bulb or element is in fact dry.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] WMO provides a 23-page chapter on the measurement of temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The thermodynamic wet-bulb temperature is a thermodynamic property of a mixture of air and water vapor.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The value indicated by a wet-bulb thermometer often provides an adequate approximation of the thermodynamic wet-bulb temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The accuracy of a simple wet-bulb thermometer depends on how fast air passes over the bulb and how well the thermometer is shielded from the radiant temperature of its surroundings.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Speeds up to 5,000 ft/min (~60 mph, 25.4 m/s) are best but it may be dangerous to move a thermometer at that speed.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Errors up to 15% can occur if the air movement is too slow or if there is too much radiant heat present (from sunlight, for example).
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] A wet bulb temperature taken with air moving at about 1–2 m/s is referred to as a **screen temperature**, whereas a temperature taken with air moving about 3.5 m/s or more is referred to as **sling temperature**.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] A psychrometer is a device that includes both a dry-bulb and a wet-bulb thermometer.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] A **sling psychrometer** requires manual operation to create the airflow over the bulbs, but a **powered psychrometer** includes a fan for this function.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Knowing both the dry-bulb temperature (DBT) and wet-bulb temperature (WBT), one can determine the relative humidity (RH) from the psychrometric chart appropriate to the air pressure.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The saturation temperature of the moisture present in the sample of air, it can also be defined as the temperature at which the vapour changes into liquid (condensation).
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Usually the level at which water vapor changes into liquid marks the base of the cloud in the atmosphere hence called condensation level.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] So the temperature value that allows this process (condensation) to take place is called the 'dew point temperature'.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] A simplified definition is the temperature at which the water vapour turns into "dew" (Chamunoda Zambuko 2012).
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Specific humidity is defined as the mass of water vapor as a proportion of the mass of the moist air sample (including both dry air and the water vapor); it is closely related to humidity ratio and always lower in value.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The mass of water vapor per unit mass of dry air containing the water vapor.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] This quantity is also known as the water vapor density.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Is a ratio, expressed in percent, of the amount of atmospheric moisture present relative to the amount that would be present if the air was saturated.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Analogous to the specific enthalpy of a pure substance.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] In psychrometrics, the term quantifies the total energy of both the dry air and water vapour per kilogram of dry air.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Analogous to the specific volume of a pure substance.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] However, in psychrometrics, the term quantifies the total volume of both the dry air and water vapour per unit mass of dry air.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The **psychrometric ratio** is the ratio of the heat transfer coefficient to the product of mass transfer coefficient and humid heat at a wetted surface.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The psychrometric ratio is an important property in the area of psychrometry, as it relates the absolute humidity and saturation humidity to the difference between the dry bulb temperature and the adiabatic saturation temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Mixtures of air and water vapor are the most common systems encountered in psychrometry.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The psychrometric ratio of air-water vapor mixtures is approximately unity, which implies that the difference between the adiabatic saturation temperature and wet bulb temperature of air-water vapor mixtures is small.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] This property of air-water vapor systems simplifies drying and cooling calculations often performed using psychrometric relationships.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] A psychrometric chart is a graph of the thermodynamic parameters of moist air at a constant pressure, often equated to an elevation relative to sea level.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The ASHRAE-style psychrometric chart, shown here, was pioneered by Willis Carrier in 1904.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] It depicts these parameters and is thus a graphical equation of state.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The psychrometric chart allows all the parameters of some moist air to be determined from any three independent parameters, one of which must be the pressure.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Changes in *state*, such as when two air streams mix, can be modeled easily and somewhat graphically using the correct psychrometric chart for the location's air pressure or elevation relative to sea level.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] For locations at not more than 2000 ft (600 m) of altitude it is common practice to use the sea-level psychrometric chart.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] In the *ω*-*t* chart, the dry bulb temperature (*t*) appears as the abscissa (horizontal axis) and the humidity ratio (*ω*) appear as the ordinate (vertical axis).
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] A chart is valid for a given air pressure (or elevation above sea level).
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] From any two independent ones of the six parameters dry bulb temperature, wet bulb temperature, relative humidity, humidity ratio, specific enthalpy, and specific volume, all the others can be determined.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] There are $\left({6 \atop 2}\right)=15$ possible combinations of independent and derived parameters.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The region above the saturation curve is a two-phase region that represents a mixture of saturated moist air and liquid water, in thermal equilibrium.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The protractor on the upper left of the chart has two scales.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The inner scale represents sensible-total heat ratio (SHF).
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The outer scale gives the ratio of enthalpy difference to humidity difference.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] This is used to establish the slope of a condition line between two processes.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The horizontal component of the condition line is the change in sensible heat while the vertical component is the change in latent heat.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Psychrometric charts are available in SI (metric) and IP (U.S./Imperial) units.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] They are also available in low and high temperature ranges and for different pressures.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] A common variation of this problem is determining the final humidity of air leaving an air conditioner evaporator coil then heated to a higher temperature.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Assume that the temperature leaving the coil is 10°C (50°F) and is heated to room temperature (not mixed with room air), which is found by following the horizontal humidity ratio from the dew point or saturation line to the room dry bulb temperature line and reading the relative humidity.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] In typical practice the conditioned air is mixed with room air that is being infiltrated with outside air.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The "Mollier *i*-*x*" (Enthalpy – Humidity Mixing Ratio) diagram, developed by Richard Mollier in 1923, is an alternative psychrometric chart, preferred by many users in Germany, Austria, Switzerland, the Netherlands, Belgium, France, Scandinavia, Eastern Europe, and Russia.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The underlying psychrometric parameter data for the psychrometric chart and the Mollier diagram are identical.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] At first glance there is little resemblance between the charts, but if the chart is rotated by ninety degrees and looked at in a mirror the resemblance becomes apparent.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The Mollier diagram coordinates are enthalpy and humidity ratio.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The enthalpy coordinate is *skewed* and the lines of constant enthalpy are parallel and evenly spaced.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] The ASHRAE psychrometric charts since 1961 use similar plotting coordinates.
[src:humidity-sensors/psychrometrics] Some psychrometric charts use *dry-bulb temperature* and *humidity ratio* coordinates.
